242
00:18:07,019 --> 00:18:10,045
COTTLE: Your fluid
and electrolyte levels
are stable.

243
00:18:10,323 --> 00:18:12,655
I think the baby's
gonna be fine.

244
00:18:12,959 --> 00:18:15,291
You do have a cracked rib,
though,

245
00:18:15,361 --> 00:18:19,627
a hairline fracture,
which means it's gonna hurt
like hell for a while.

246
00:18:21,267 --> 00:18:24,464
But I'm not seeing
any signs of permanent damage
from the attack.

247
00:18:29,642 --> 00:18:32,873
The attack.
Is that what we're
calling it now?

248
00:18:33,412 --> 00:18:35,107
They were not
from the Galactica.

249
00:18:40,486 --> 00:18:43,649
They were from the Pegasus.
So what?

250
00:18:47,093 --> 00:18:48,583
What about Helo and the Chief?

251
00:18:50,463 --> 00:18:52,431
I heard a rumor
they're gonna be executed.

252
00:18:55,801 --> 00:18:57,234
I'm not gonna
let that happen.

253
00:18:58,371 --> 00:18:59,668
Well,
how're you gonna do that?

254
00:19:00,273 --> 00:19:02,503
Isn't Adm. Cain in command?

255
00:19:04,877 --> 00:19:06,242
What happened to you...

256
00:19:06,345 --> 00:19:07,972
COTTLE: Was unforgivable.

257
00:19:11,684 --> 00:19:14,312
...happened aboard my ship,
on my watch,

258
00:19:14,620 --> 00:19:16,212
and it's my responsibility.

259
00:19:19,325 --> 00:19:21,816
So I just want you to know
that I personally apologize.

260
00:19:24,163 --> 00:19:26,290
See that she's okay,
then back into her cell.

261
00:19:48,054 --> 00:19:49,851
Aren't we supposed to be dead?

262
00:19:49,922 --> 00:19:52,584
Admiral said
execution in an hour.
It's been at least two.

263
00:19:52,658 --> 00:19:53,989
Hey, I'm not complaining.

264
00:19:55,528 --> 00:19:56,790
COMPUTER:
ID confirmed.

265
00:19:56,862 --> 00:19:58,352
(DOOR OPENlNG)

266
00:20:05,972 --> 00:20:09,237
So, just how many different
kinds of stupid are you?

267
00:20:12,478 --> 00:20:13,968
More than we can count.

268
00:20:15,281 --> 00:20:17,010
What's going on, Captain?

269
00:20:17,116 --> 00:20:19,482
Good news,
you're not dead yet.

270
00:20:19,885 --> 00:20:23,218
Bad news,
it's a delay, not a pardon.

271
00:20:24,757 --> 00:20:26,054
There's a big op coming up,

272
00:20:26,125 --> 00:20:28,286
and the firing squad's
on hold till it's over.

273
00:20:29,862 --> 00:20:34,322
Yeah, the old man went
to the mat for you guys
on this one, and then some.

274
00:20:35,534 --> 00:20:37,968
We were this close
to a shooting war
with the Pegasus.

275
00:20:40,506 --> 00:20:41,871
Frak me.

276
00:20:41,974 --> 00:20:45,000
What the hell's going on?
I thought the Cylons
were the enemy.

277
00:20:45,077 --> 00:20:46,169
Yeah. Now it's us.

278
00:21:01,160 --> 00:21:02,354
What's wrong, Gaius?

279
00:21:05,097 --> 00:21:06,086
Nothing.

280
00:21:08,668 --> 00:21:09,896
Nothing.

281
00:21:14,140 --> 00:21:16,005
I suppose I just

282
00:21:17,510 --> 00:21:18,738
Iost interest.

283
00:21:21,347 --> 00:21:23,781
In me?
No, not in you. In...

284
00:21:26,185 --> 00:21:28,449
In this. In this place.

285
00:21:31,924 --> 00:21:34,119
I suppose I just don't
really miss it anymore.

286
00:21:37,563 --> 00:21:38,655
You know what I miss?

287
00:21:42,868 --> 00:21:44,062
Sports.

288
00:21:45,604 --> 00:21:46,764
You're joking.

289
00:21:46,839 --> 00:21:47,828
No.

290
00:21:50,776 --> 00:21:53,939
I used to go
to the pyramid court
just before game time.

291
00:21:54,013 --> 00:21:55,139
Scalp two tickets.

292
00:21:56,315 --> 00:22:00,149
If I timed it right,
I'd just be sitting down
at the horn.

293
00:22:00,753 --> 00:22:02,015
Sit back.

294
00:22:02,521 --> 00:22:05,217
Let the energy of the crowd
flow over me.

295
00:22:05,291 --> 00:22:07,384
Waves and waves of emotion.

296
00:22:09,161 --> 00:22:11,026
Like electric current.

297
00:22:13,032 --> 00:22:14,465
Why did you get two tickets?

298
00:22:15,167 --> 00:22:17,260
One for me and one for you.

299
00:22:17,870 --> 00:22:19,497
I knew I'd never
get you to go.

300
00:22:19,572 --> 00:22:21,665
Pyramid was far too lowbrow
for you. But...

301
00:22:25,211 --> 00:22:27,406
I always liked to feel
that you were there with me.

302
00:22:28,814 --> 00:22:30,304
(DOOR OPENlNG)

303
00:22:30,916 --> 00:22:32,543
COMPUTER:
ID confirmed.

304
00:22:46,398 --> 00:22:48,992
Well, I see that you
got it to eat.

305
00:22:50,536 --> 00:22:52,629
That's progress, I suppose.

306
00:22:54,073 --> 00:22:57,201
Can you get it to roll over,
beg?

307
00:22:57,643 --> 00:22:58,632
(SCOFFlNG)

308
00:23:01,046 --> 00:23:03,241
See what it
can make of these.

309
00:23:09,088 --> 00:23:12,615
You know, this thing
used to sit in our mess

310
00:23:14,059 --> 00:23:17,187
and eat our food
and listen to our stories.

311
00:23:19,398 --> 00:23:22,595
Didn't you?
You just sat there,

312
00:23:24,770 --> 00:23:29,173
Iistening to us,
pretending to be our friend.
Didn't you?

313
00:23:29,375 --> 00:23:30,967
Admiral, please!

314
00:23:31,710 --> 00:23:34,838
Any physical contact
with the subject
will only help

315
00:23:34,914 --> 00:23:36,643
to set my efforts back
at this point.

316
00:23:45,658 --> 00:23:47,649
Find out about that ship.

317
00:24:08,013 --> 00:24:09,776
(SCREAMlNG)

318
00:24:37,509 --> 00:24:38,999
I want to die.

319
00:24:42,214 --> 00:24:43,374
Will you help me do that?

320
00:24:46,852 --> 00:24:48,820
Will you kill me, please?

321
00:24:50,756 --> 00:24:52,246
(GlNA SOBBlNG)

322
00:25:03,302 --> 00:25:06,328
I'm just still getting up
to speed on the way you do
things around here,

323
00:25:06,405 --> 00:25:08,839
but I'm reasonably sure
that we can have
all the birds in the air

324
00:25:08,908 --> 00:25:10,102
for the attack thing, sure.

325
00:25:11,076 --> 00:25:12,703
I mean, yes, sir.

326
00:25:13,379 --> 00:25:14,403
Thank you, Chief.

327
00:25:16,081 --> 00:25:17,343
MAN 1: Hey! Hey!

328
00:25:17,416 --> 00:25:18,440
(CRASHlNG)

329
00:25:18,517 --> 00:25:20,542
MAN 2: I got it, I got it.

330
00:25:20,619 --> 00:25:22,519
MAN 1: Give me a hand.
Cally.

331
00:25:26,392 --> 00:25:28,019
Laird's not military, is he?

332
00:25:28,794 --> 00:25:30,091
No, sir.

333
00:25:30,162 --> 00:25:32,824
He was a civilian
aeronautical engineer

334
00:25:32,898 --> 00:25:35,423
on a ship called the Scylla.

335
00:25:35,501 --> 00:25:36,763
Civilian?

336
00:25:38,404 --> 00:25:40,429
Do you know how he got
on the Pegasus?

337
00:25:41,740 --> 00:25:45,540
Scuttlebutt is that
the Pegasus used to have
a civilian fleet,

338
00:25:46,111 --> 00:25:47,635
but something
happened to them.

339
00:25:50,549 --> 00:25:51,538
Thank you.

340
00:26:03,896 --> 00:26:06,023
Laird's ship was the Scylla.

341
00:26:10,903 --> 00:26:14,737
The Scylla was
a civilian transport.

342
00:26:16,976 --> 00:26:20,412
We found her
and a few other civies

343
00:26:20,479 --> 00:26:22,709
about a week after the attack.

344
00:26:27,953 --> 00:26:29,147
They were good ships.

345
00:26:29,922 --> 00:26:32,254
FTL drives and weapons, even.

346
00:26:33,292 --> 00:26:37,126
A lot of potential
spare parts that we
could use on Pegasus.

347
00:26:39,231 --> 00:26:41,893
So the Admiral
made a decision.

348
00:26:43,702 --> 00:26:47,138
Military needs are a priority.

349
00:26:50,075 --> 00:26:51,633
You stripped them.

350
00:26:51,710 --> 00:26:54,042
You stripped the ships
for parts.

351
00:26:56,615 --> 00:26:58,583
Sweet mother of Artemis.

352
00:27:01,186 --> 00:27:02,778
How much equipment
did you take?

353
00:27:05,691 --> 00:27:06,851
You take their jump drives?

354
00:27:11,263 --> 00:27:13,288
Left all those people
marooned out there?

355
00:27:13,365 --> 00:27:14,389
No, not all.

356
00:27:17,669 --> 00:27:21,935
Adm. Cain looked over
the passenger list
and she made a decision

357
00:27:22,007 --> 00:27:25,408
about who was valuable
and who wasn't.

358
00:27:33,385 --> 00:27:35,353
Scylla was the toughest.

359
00:27:36,321 --> 00:27:38,653
Laird and 15
other men and women.

360
00:27:38,724 --> 00:27:40,316
They were all...

361
00:27:40,659 --> 00:27:43,059
All traveling
with their families,

362
00:27:43,128 --> 00:27:45,289
wives, husbands, children.

363
00:27:45,664 --> 00:27:47,325
The selectees

364
00:27:48,267 --> 00:27:51,168
refused to go.
There was resistance.

365
00:27:53,072 --> 00:27:55,097
So, the order came down

366
00:27:56,975 --> 00:28:01,469
to shoot the family
of anyone who refused to come.

367
00:28:04,383 --> 00:28:05,714
So we did.

368
00:28:07,352 --> 00:28:10,981
Two families. We put them
up against the bulkhead

369
00:28:13,592 --> 00:28:15,219
and we shot them.

370
00:28:29,274 --> 00:28:31,469
The CAG's work is never done.

371
00:28:33,245 --> 00:28:35,042
Hi. How're you doing?

372
00:28:37,282 --> 00:28:39,910
Oh, you mean
apart from being demoted,

373
00:28:40,486 --> 00:28:43,387
finding myself working
for one of my pilots?

374
00:28:45,691 --> 00:28:47,454
Great. Never better.

375
00:28:50,729 --> 00:28:53,220
You know I had nothing
to do with that, right?

376
00:28:53,298 --> 00:28:54,492
Never thought you did.

377
00:29:01,807 --> 00:29:04,298
I just checked in
on Helo and Tyrol.

378
00:29:05,777 --> 00:29:07,005
They're hanging tight for now.

379
00:29:07,946 --> 00:29:09,038
Good.

380
00:29:11,550 --> 00:29:13,347
Help me plan this op.

381
00:29:13,852 --> 00:29:15,615
I've been staring
at this roster...

382
00:29:18,257 --> 00:29:21,317
Do you want to just carry on
as if nothing's happened?

383
00:29:21,393 --> 00:29:23,224
Lee, she's in command.
What do you wanna do?

384
00:29:24,263 --> 00:29:26,356
There's nothing we can do.

385
00:29:29,568 --> 00:29:31,798
I thought you might like
a fresh set of clothes.

386
00:30:21,653 --> 00:30:25,612
Were you aware of your
true nature as a Cylon
when you boarded the ship

387
00:30:26,658 --> 00:30:29,855
or would you describe
yourself as a sleeper agent?

388
00:30:33,398 --> 00:30:35,059
I knew what I was.

389
00:30:36,935 --> 00:30:40,098
I was a soldier.
I had a mission,
I carried it out.

390
00:30:43,041 --> 00:30:45,305
I thought that when it was
done, I was going to die.

391
00:30:46,411 --> 00:30:48,140
That you would kill me.

392
00:30:49,881 --> 00:30:53,783
Then l... Then I would
download into a new body.

393
00:30:54,953 --> 00:30:56,284
Be reborn.

394
00:30:56,922 --> 00:30:58,822
But you didn't kill me.

395
00:30:59,458 --> 00:31:01,619
The things you did to me...

396
00:31:01,693 --> 00:31:05,026
What they did to you
was wrong, evil.

397
00:31:06,498 --> 00:31:07,795
But I'm not one of them.

398
00:31:09,801 --> 00:31:11,063
You have to believe me.

399
00:31:13,238 --> 00:31:17,072
Things are going to get
better for you
from this moment on.

400
00:31:18,644 --> 00:31:19,975
I promise.

401
00:31:20,145 --> 00:31:23,080
I don't want things
to get better. I want to die.

402
00:31:25,250 --> 00:31:27,343
But you know you can't die.

403
00:31:28,453 --> 00:31:29,750
You do know that, don't you?

404
00:31:31,556 --> 00:31:35,185
Your consciousness will merely
transfer, and you'll wake up
in another body.

405
00:31:36,495 --> 00:31:37,985
Not if you destroy that.

406
00:31:40,699 --> 00:31:41,996
What, this?

407
00:31:44,169 --> 00:31:47,104
This ship? Tell me,

408
00:31:51,810 --> 00:31:54,335
what's so important
about this ship?

409
00:31:58,550 --> 00:32:01,815
The Cylons call this
their Resurrection ship.

410
00:32:01,887 --> 00:32:04,617
At the moment,
we are too far away
from the Cylon home world

411
00:32:04,690 --> 00:32:06,351
for the normal
downloading process to work.

412
00:32:06,425 --> 00:32:08,825
Which is why
they built this ship.

413
00:32:09,061 --> 00:32:12,997
It contains the entire
apparatus necessary
for Cylon resurrection.

414
00:32:13,832 --> 00:32:16,460
Now, this ship has been
traveling with the fleet,

415
00:32:16,535 --> 00:32:18,469
trailing Galactica
for the last several months.

416
00:32:19,638 --> 00:32:20,764
So it's a safety net.

417
00:32:21,506 --> 00:32:23,474
A place where they fall
back to when they die.

418
00:32:24,443 --> 00:32:26,274
And if they lose
their safety net...

419
00:32:28,246 --> 00:32:30,908
Then any Cylon
who dies out here...

420
00:32:30,982 --> 00:32:32,472
Would be dead.

421
00:32:34,353 --> 00:32:36,378
As in, really dead.

422
00:32:39,291 --> 00:32:41,259
And I dare say
they won't like that.

423
00:32:41,893 --> 00:32:43,121
No, sir.

424
00:32:44,296 --> 00:32:45,820
They might even
stop chasing us.

425
00:32:46,698 --> 00:32:49,428
Why risk getting killed
if you can't just wake up
all nice and cozy

426
00:32:49,501 --> 00:32:50,798
in a brand-new body?

427
00:32:53,772 --> 00:32:55,467
Doctor, I think
you've just identified

428
00:32:55,540 --> 00:32:57,201
the most important ship
in the galaxy.

429
00:33:07,919 --> 00:33:11,355
I have good days
and bad days,
but don't look so worried,

430
00:33:11,423 --> 00:33:13,186
I'm not dying today.

431
00:33:15,127 --> 00:33:16,754
I wasn't worried.

432
00:33:18,363 --> 00:33:20,228
What can I do for you?

433
00:33:21,767 --> 00:33:23,792
You were right about Cain.

434
00:33:25,270 --> 00:33:28,205
Pegasus had a civilian fleet
with her.

435
00:33:29,040 --> 00:33:30,530
Fifteen ships.

436
00:33:33,011 --> 00:33:37,107
Cain stripped them
for parts, supplies,

437
00:33:38,750 --> 00:33:39,944
people.

438
00:33:42,154 --> 00:33:45,612
I wish I could say
I was surprised,
but it's who she is.

439
00:33:46,091 --> 00:33:48,491
She's playing for keeps.
You gotta do the same.

440
00:33:49,428 --> 00:33:51,123
What's gotten into you?

441
00:33:51,196 --> 00:33:52,185
What?

442
00:33:53,098 --> 00:33:55,328
You've become
so bloody-minded.

443
00:33:57,002 --> 00:33:59,562
I know that as long
as Cain lives,

444
00:34:00,705 --> 00:34:03,037
your survival is at risk.
I know that.

445
00:34:03,108 --> 00:34:04,439
(COUGHlNG)

446
00:34:21,660 --> 00:34:23,389
What can I get you?

447
00:34:24,896 --> 00:34:26,261
A new body.

448
00:34:28,834 --> 00:34:31,997
Perhaps one of those
young Cylon models

449
00:34:32,070 --> 00:34:34,163
from the Resurrection ship?

450
00:34:34,639 --> 00:34:36,766
I can't see you as a blonde.

451
00:34:38,577 --> 00:34:40,408
You'd be surprised.

452
00:34:49,154 --> 00:34:50,451
I'll see you tomorrow?

453
00:34:50,522 --> 00:34:51,614
Mmm-hmm.

454
00:35:01,967 --> 00:35:03,298
Commander,

455
00:35:05,170 --> 00:35:07,400
she won't hesitate
to kill you.

456
00:35:09,207 --> 00:35:10,196
Don't let her.

457
00:35:30,695 --> 00:35:33,027
You know,
when we get out of here,

458
00:35:34,366 --> 00:35:36,493
I'm gonna make some changes.

459
00:35:38,770 --> 00:35:39,862
Yeah?

460
00:35:40,305 --> 00:35:41,636
Like what?

461
00:35:43,174 --> 00:35:44,664
Me and Sharon.

462
00:35:48,113 --> 00:35:49,444
It's done.

463
00:35:54,119 --> 00:35:56,952
I mean, really done.
I can't do it anymore.

464
00:35:58,223 --> 00:36:00,123
I mean, don't get me wrong.

465
00:36:00,292 --> 00:36:02,055
LT, what we did,

466
00:36:03,361 --> 00:36:06,455
I would do again
in a heartbeat.

467
00:36:09,768 --> 00:36:11,429
I gotta let it go.

468
00:36:13,605 --> 00:36:15,698
I so thought I'd let go.

469
00:36:16,041 --> 00:36:17,133
Yeah,

470
00:36:18,376 --> 00:36:20,173
I know what you mean.

471
00:36:21,746 --> 00:36:22,804
You?

472
00:36:23,114 --> 00:36:24,376
Yeah, me.

473
00:36:25,383 --> 00:36:29,217
What, you think I don't have
second thoughts sometimes?

474
00:36:31,222 --> 00:36:34,749
You think I don't wonder if
I'm losing my frakking mind?

475
00:36:35,193 --> 00:36:38,185
I'm in love with a woman
I know isn't a woman.

476
00:36:42,267 --> 00:36:44,360
I'm having a baby that's...

477
00:36:44,836 --> 00:36:48,169
That's what, half machine?

478
00:36:57,449 --> 00:36:59,815
You really do love her,
don't you?

479
00:36:59,884 --> 00:37:00,976
Yeah.

480
00:37:02,621 --> 00:37:03,952
Yes, I do.

481
00:37:06,458 --> 00:37:08,449
And I can't let go of it.

482
00:37:11,796 --> 00:37:15,323
But if you can, let her go.

483
00:38:16,394 --> 00:38:20,330
Our primary objective
